<DOC><DOCNO> AP880319-0196 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-19-88 0245EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-PostalInstantPress     03-19 0165</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Postal Instant Press,0170</SECOND><HEAD>PIP in Talks With New Suitor as Buyout Bid Expires</HEAD><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Postal Instant Press Inc., the nation'slargest franchiser of printing centers, said Friday amanagement-led offer to buy the company has expired and it isnegotiating to be acquired by another suitor for a higher price.   The company said it received the new offer of $17.50 per share,or $68.25 million, on Wednesday from an investor group that itdidn't identify.   That is 50 cents a share higher than what was being offered bythe management group and the Chicago-based leveraged-buyout concernGolder, Thoma andamp; Cressey. The management group made its offer Feb.19.   In addition, PIP said the new suitor has indicated it may raiseits offer after studying non-public information provided by the LosAngeles-based company that has about 1,000 printing centersfranchised in the United States, Canada and the United Kingdom.   Last year, PIP escaped a hostile bid by Tarrytown, N.Y.-basedKane-Miller Corp.</TEXT></DOC>